00:08:13.990 --> 00:08:16.900 align:middle line:84%
Although we'll say a little bit
about putting the world pieces

00:08:16.900 --> 00:08:19.070 align:middle line:90%
together at the very end.

00:08:19.070 --> 00:08:22.150 align:middle line:84%
So here's the notation,
which is largely

00:08:22.150 --> 00:08:25.900 align:middle line:84%
a review because you have
seen almost all of it before.

00:08:25.900 --> 00:08:29.170 align:middle line:84%
When we write down an economy,
we mean the commodity space,

00:08:29.170 --> 00:08:32.470 align:middle line:84%
in this case, capital L, a
finite number of commodities.

00:08:32.470 --> 00:08:34.690 align:middle line:90%
I is the number of consumers.

00:08:34.690 --> 00:08:36.460 align:middle line:90%
J is the number of firms--

00:08:36.460 --> 00:08:37.840 align:middle line:90%
finite for each.

00:08:37.840 --> 00:08:41.679 align:middle line:84%
Household or consumer,
I, has a consumption set.

00:08:41.679 --> 00:08:46.060 align:middle line:84%
And preferences over bundles
in the consumption set, as for,

00:08:46.060 --> 00:08:48.850 align:middle line:84%
example, represented
by a utility function.

00:08:48.850 --> 00:08:52.480 align:middle line:84%
Each firm, J, has a technology
production possibility

00:08:52.480 --> 00:08:55.280 align:middle line:84%
set in the same L
dimensional space.

00:08:55.280 --> 00:08:59.530 align:middle line:84%
And the economy has
exogenously given endowments,

00:08:59.530 --> 00:09:02.770 align:middle line:84%
according to this L
dimensional endowment vector,

00:09:02.770 --> 00:09:06.060 align:middle line:84%
with the bars being
the aggregates.

00:09:06.060 --> 00:09:08.490 align:middle line:90%
So that's the economy.

00:09:08.490 --> 00:09:11.580 align:middle line:84%
Now, in, say, a private
ownership economy, we

00:09:11.580 --> 00:09:15.040 align:middle line:84%
have to specify, in
addition, who owns what.

00:09:15.040 --> 00:09:20.070 align:middle line:84%
So we imagine that consumer
I has an endowment vector, L

00:09:20.070 --> 00:09:23.790 align:middle line:84%
dimensional, subscript
I, for consumer, I.

00:09:23.790 --> 00:09:27.090 align:middle line:84%
And it is the sum of
these endowments over all

00:09:27.090 --> 00:09:30.840 align:middle line:84%
the household that adds
up to the omega bar L

00:09:30.840 --> 00:09:33.720 align:middle line:84%
dimensional endowment vector
on the previous slide.

00:09:33.720 --> 00:09:37.830 align:middle line:84%
Aggregates naturally come from
the individual's ownership.

00:09:37.830 --> 00:09:41.100 align:middle line:84%
Each consumer, in addition
to having endowments,

00:09:41.100 --> 00:09:44.650 align:middle line:84%
has some share of
the profits of firms.

00:09:44.650 --> 00:09:49.860 align:middle line:84%
So theta, IJ, being the
share that household, I, has,

00:09:49.860 --> 00:09:51.390 align:middle line:90%
of J's profits.

00:09:51.390 --> 00:09:54.670 align:middle line:84%
So these are meant to be
a division of the profit.

00:09:54.670 --> 00:09:58.620 align:middle line:84%
So the sum of the shares
over households, I,

00:09:58.620 --> 00:10:01.290 align:middle line:84%
for a given firm,
J, add up to 1.

00:10:01.290 --> 00:10:02.970 align:middle line:90%
Everything gets distributed.

00:10:02.970 --> 00:10:07.800 align:middle line:84%
And household I is getting theta
IJ of pi J, for firm, J. Now,

00:10:07.800 --> 00:10:10.630 align:middle line:84%
pi J is obviously an
endogenous object.

00:10:10.630 --> 00:10:14.160 align:middle line:84%
It could be 0 if there were
constant returns to scale.

00:10:14.160 --> 00:10:17.370 align:middle line:84%
It could be positive if
there are diminishing returns

00:10:17.370 --> 00:10:18.120 align:middle line:90%
to scale.

00:10:18.120 --> 00:10:23.010 align:middle line:84%
And also, when we did risk and
return in village economies,

00:10:23.010 --> 00:10:26.940 align:middle line:84%
we kind of naturally had
an interesting and relevant

00:10:26.940 --> 00:10:30.900 align:middle line:84%
special case that household
I gets all the profits

00:10:30.900 --> 00:10:33.390 align:middle line:84%
from the activities
that it undertakes.

00:10:33.390 --> 00:10:36.330 align:middle line:84%
In that case, there was a
household, I, and a firm,

00:10:36.330 --> 00:10:38.790 align:middle line:90%
I. It was the same entity.

00:10:38.790 --> 00:10:41.190 align:middle line:84%
And household I was
getting theta IJ

00:10:41.190 --> 00:10:46.020 align:middle line:84%
equal to 1 of its own
profits, as a special case.

00:10:46.020 --> 00:10:48.840 align:middle line:84%
But general equilibrium
theory usually

00:10:48.840 --> 00:10:50.700 align:middle line:90%
allows something more general.

00:10:50.700 --> 00:10:53.520 align:middle line:84%
And you could think of
this literally as a market

00:10:53.520 --> 00:10:56.850 align:middle line:84%
economy, where the shares are
equity shares being traded.

00:10:56.850 --> 00:10:59.640 align:middle line:84%
And all of the
dividends are claimed

00:10:59.640 --> 00:11:01.380 align:middle line:90%
by the ownership of shares.

00:11:01.380 --> 00:11:04.380 align:middle line:84%
OK, so a private
ownership economy

00:11:04.380 --> 00:11:06.900 align:middle line:84%
has a summary of
the consumption,

00:11:06.900 --> 00:11:09.210 align:middle line:84%
set preferences,
endowments of consumer

00:11:09.210 --> 00:11:12.960 align:middle line:84%
I, the production sets of
all the house firms, J,

00:11:12.960 --> 00:11:16.060 align:middle line:90%
and the shares, theta IJ.

00:11:16.060 --> 00:11:19.080 align:middle line:84%
Now we get to the
big definition here.

00:11:19.080 --> 00:11:22.050 align:middle line:84%
In this L dimensional
commodity space,

00:11:22.050 --> 00:11:26.790 align:middle line:84%
a price vector, p, is the price
of all the commodities, inputs,

00:11:26.790 --> 00:11:28.320 align:middle line:90%
and outputs, and everything.

00:11:28.320 --> 00:11:31.920 align:middle line:84%
And a Walrasian equilibrium,
or competitive equilibrium

00:11:31.920 --> 00:11:34.950 align:middle line:84%
for short, for this
private ownership economy,

00:11:34.950 --> 00:11:39.750 align:middle line:84%
is a specification of
allocations with stars on them,

00:11:39.750 --> 00:11:42.900 align:middle line:84%
x and y star, for
consumers and firms--

00:11:42.900 --> 00:11:49.020 align:middle line:84%
and a price vector star here
because it's a special price.

00:11:49.020 --> 00:11:52.200 align:middle line:84%
Allocations and prices have
the special properties.

00:11:52.200 --> 00:11:55.890 align:middle line:84%
Each firm, J, has y
star J as the maximum

00:11:55.890 --> 00:11:59.550 align:middle line:84%
of the firm's problem, which
is to maximize profits.

00:11:59.550 --> 00:12:03.660 align:middle line:84%
Hence, at y star, the valuation
of outputs less inputs

00:12:03.660 --> 00:12:06.990 align:middle line:84%
is weakly greater than it
would be for any other choice

00:12:06.990 --> 00:12:08.370 align:middle line:90%
of production vector.

00:12:08.370 --> 00:12:12.390 align:middle line:84%
Each consumer, i, is maximizing
relative to the preference

00:12:12.390 --> 00:12:16.410 align:middle line:84%
ordering on bundles in the
consumption set, but also

00:12:16.410 --> 00:12:17.910 align:middle line:84%
subject to the
budget constraint,

00:12:17.910 --> 00:12:21.720 align:middle line:84%
that expenditures at price
p star, for any xi that

00:12:21.720 --> 00:12:23.760 align:middle line:90%
could potentially be chosen--

00:12:23.760 --> 00:12:27.010 align:middle line:84%
cannot exceed the
right hand side,

00:12:27.010 --> 00:12:28.920 align:middle line:84%
which is the private
ownership part.

00:12:28.920 --> 00:12:32.490 align:middle line:84%
So omega i, being the
endowments of consumer,

00:12:32.490 --> 00:12:36.870 align:middle line:84%
i, evaluated at price p star,
that dot is inner product.

00:12:36.870 --> 00:12:42.060 align:middle line:84%
And again, household i's claim
on the profits of firm, J.

00:12:42.060 --> 00:12:44.610 align:middle line:84%
And the final property
is that the allocation

00:12:44.610 --> 00:12:45.495 align:middle line:90%
has to be feasible.

00:12:45.495 --> 00:12:49.800 align:middle line:84%
And you can just read this as
demand cannot exceed supply,

00:12:49.800 --> 00:12:52.500 align:middle line:84%
where supply includes both
the aggregated endowment

00:12:52.500 --> 00:12:54.540 align:middle line:90%
and production.

00:12:54.540 --> 00:12:57.590 align:middle line:84%
So we worked a lot with
feasibility before.

00:12:57.590 --> 00:13:00.710 align:middle line:84%
We did that when we
defined Pareto optimality.

00:13:00.710 --> 00:13:02.930 align:middle line:84%
The difference here
in general equilibrium

00:13:02.930 --> 00:13:05.150 align:middle line:84%
or Walrasian
equilibrium is we've

00:13:05.150 --> 00:13:08.690 align:middle line:84%
added this price vector
explicitly, and rewritten

00:13:08.690 --> 00:13:11.270 align:middle line:84%
consumer maximization
problem, on which we've

00:13:11.270 --> 00:13:12.410 align:middle line:90%
had several lectures.

00:13:12.410 --> 00:13:14.990 align:middle line:84%
And firms-- sorry, I
reversed the order--

00:13:14.990 --> 00:13:19.050 align:middle line:84%
firms max and
consumers max problems.

00:13:19.050 --> 00:13:22.906 align:middle line:90%
So everything's in one spot.

00:13:22.906 --> 00:13:27.320 align:middle line:84%
OK, so a classic example
is the Edgeworth Box.

00:13:27.320 --> 00:13:30.740 align:middle line:84%
We previously defined
Pareto optimal allocations

00:13:30.740 --> 00:13:34.250 align:middle line:84%
in this box, as
characterized by tangencies

00:13:34.250 --> 00:13:35.720 align:middle line:90%
of indifference curves.

00:13:35.720 --> 00:13:38.420 align:middle line:84%
Here we add one more
ingredient, that if they

00:13:38.420 --> 00:13:42.230 align:middle line:84%
start with this endowment,
and we draw a price line

00:13:42.230 --> 00:13:46.790 align:middle line:84%
through the endowment, then
each consumer is maximizing

00:13:46.790 --> 00:13:49.680 align:middle line:90%
utility, subject to its budget.

00:13:49.680 --> 00:13:56.550 align:middle line:84%
So consumer 1 here has the
normal-looking budget line.

00:13:56.550 --> 00:14:01.130 align:middle line:84%
And coming from the endowment
and the tangency at x star

00:14:01.130 --> 00:14:02.480 align:middle line:90%
would be the maximum.

00:14:02.480 --> 00:14:06.500 align:middle line:84%
You may remember consumer
2 up here on the northeast

00:14:06.500 --> 00:14:09.920 align:middle line:84%
is moving to the southwest in
terms of increased utility,

00:14:09.920 --> 00:14:12.590 align:middle line:84%
and is also maximizing
utility, which

00:14:12.590 --> 00:14:15.780 align:middle line:84%
is achieved by a tangency on
that consumer's budget line.

00:14:15.780 --> 00:14:18.560 align:middle line:84%
So this line here is
doing double duty.

00:14:18.560 --> 00:14:20.960 align:middle line:84%
It's a budget line
for each household.

00:14:20.960 --> 00:14:25.010 align:middle line:84%
But the perspective is
at or below consumer 1,

00:14:25.010 --> 00:14:28.520 align:middle line:84%
at or above the
line for consumer 2.

00:14:28.520 --> 00:14:31.850 align:middle line:84%
And here you're seeing the
star allocations, which

00:14:31.850 --> 00:14:34.010 align:middle line:90%
are a competitive equilibrium.

00:14:34.010 --> 00:14:37.700 align:middle line:84%
Everything in the box adds up to
the aggregates by construction.

00:14:37.700 --> 00:14:39.170 align:middle line:90%
There is no production.

00:14:39.170 --> 00:14:41.360 align:middle line:90%
They're all maximizing utility.

00:14:41.360 --> 00:14:45.680 align:middle line:84%
And the price vector is
characterized by the slope

00:14:45.680 --> 00:14:47.300 align:middle line:90%
of this budget line.

00:14:47.300 --> 00:14:50.900 align:middle line:84%
Now, we could go on with
a lot more interesting,

00:14:50.900 --> 00:14:54.710 align:middle line:84%
and some nonstandard pictures,
of the Edgeworth Box.

00:14:54.710 --> 00:14:58.160 align:middle line:84%
But we're going to save a lot
of that for another lecture.

00:14:58.160 --> 00:15:00.740 align:middle line:84%
Here, I defined
Walrasian equilibrium.

00:15:00.740 --> 00:15:04.670 align:middle line:84%
I wanted to find something
similar but not identical.

00:15:04.670 --> 00:15:08.030 align:middle line:84%
It's a price equilibrium
with transfers.

00:15:08.030 --> 00:15:11.060 align:middle line:84%
So here, the idea is
that the right hand

00:15:11.060 --> 00:15:14.030 align:middle line:90%
side is a wealth assignment.

00:15:14.030 --> 00:15:16.730 align:middle line:84%
Household, i, has
wealth, w sub i.

00:15:16.730 --> 00:15:18.903 align:middle line:90%
So the rest is similar.

00:15:18.903 --> 00:15:20.820 align:middle line:84%
We're going to have an
allocation with stars--

00:15:20.820 --> 00:15:23.840 align:middle line:84%
a price vector, p, which
should have had stars on it

00:15:23.840 --> 00:15:25.550 align:middle line:90%
because it's a special one--

00:15:25.550 --> 00:15:28.490 align:middle line:84%
with the property,
and an assignment

00:15:28.490 --> 00:15:32.340 align:middle line:84%
of these wealth levels, such
that firms maximize profits.

00:15:32.340 --> 00:15:33.800 align:middle line:90%
That's the same as before.

00:15:33.800 --> 00:15:36.150 align:middle line:90%
Households maximize utility.

00:15:36.150 --> 00:15:40.160 align:middle line:84%
But the right hand side of the
budget is this wealth object.

00:15:40.160 --> 00:15:43.790 align:middle line:84%
And again, when we did partial
equilibrium consumer problem,

00:15:43.790 --> 00:15:45.500 align:middle line:84%
we talked about
prices and wealth.

00:15:45.500 --> 00:15:48.740 align:middle line:84%
We had income expansion
paths as wealth varied.

00:15:48.740 --> 00:15:51.080 align:middle line:84%
So this formulation
of the problem

00:15:51.080 --> 00:15:52.700 align:middle line:90%
is consistent with that.

00:15:52.700 --> 00:15:54.680 align:middle line:84%
Although in partial
equilibrium, we

00:15:54.680 --> 00:15:57.170 align:middle line:84%
didn't ask where that
wealth was coming from.

00:15:57.170 --> 00:15:58.880 align:middle line:90%
An allocation is feasible.

00:15:58.880 --> 00:16:03.360 align:middle line:84%
Again, demand cannot be greater
than the two sources of supply.

00:16:03.360 --> 00:16:06.260 align:middle line:84%
Now the wealth assignments
have to be feasible.

00:16:06.260 --> 00:16:08.270 align:middle line:84%
And here's where we
can say something

00:16:08.270 --> 00:16:09.920 align:middle line:84%
about where wealth
is coming from,

00:16:09.920 --> 00:16:12.710 align:middle line:84%
namely, the sum of the
wealths, whatever they are,

00:16:12.710 --> 00:16:17.690 align:middle line:84%
have to equal the valuation of
the aggregated endowment vector

00:16:17.690 --> 00:16:21.425 align:middle line:84%
plus the profits
of all the firms.

00:16:21.425 --> 00:16:23.300 align:middle line:84%
So somehow, this stuff
on the right hand side

00:16:23.300 --> 00:16:26.630 align:middle line:84%
gets distributed across the
households, each household, i,

00:16:26.630 --> 00:16:28.400 align:middle line:90%
getting wealth, wi.

00:16:28.400 --> 00:16:30.800 align:middle line:84%
And when we add it
up, therefore, it

00:16:30.800 --> 00:16:33.360 align:middle line:90%
sums up to the right hand side.

00:16:33.360 --> 00:16:37.970 align:middle line:84%
Now note that at the bottom
here, a particular wealth

00:16:37.970 --> 00:16:41.780 align:middle line:84%
assignment that works is what
we had on the previous slide,

00:16:41.780 --> 00:16:46.370 align:middle line:84%
namely, give household, i, the
valuation of its endowment,

00:16:46.370 --> 00:16:50.280 align:middle line:84%
plus its share of the profits
of the firms that it owns.

00:16:50.280 --> 00:16:54.680 align:middle line:84%
So in that sense, a price
equilibrium with transfers

00:16:54.680 --> 00:16:59.240 align:middle line:84%
is more general, but includes
the valuation equilibrium.

00:16:59.240 --> 00:17:03.740 align:middle line:84%
That said, the word
transfers may catch your eye.

00:17:03.740 --> 00:17:07.609 align:middle line:84%
And the idea here is that
a Walrasian equilibrium

00:17:07.609 --> 00:17:10.730 align:middle line:84%
with ownership specifies
one level of wealth.

00:17:10.730 --> 00:17:13.609 align:middle line:84%
But we could, in principle,
redistribute that wealth

00:17:13.609 --> 00:17:15.800 align:middle line:84%
by the government
with lump sum taxes

00:17:15.800 --> 00:17:20.720 align:middle line:84%
and transfers, and then look
for a new priced equilibrium.

00:17:20.720 --> 00:17:23.089 align:middle line:84%
And we will-- I think it's
on the next slide, yeah.

00:17:23.089 --> 00:17:25.760 align:middle line:84%
We will get to why
we're doing this.

00:17:25.760 --> 00:17:30.560 align:middle line:84%
Namely, any Walrasian
equilibrium is Pareto-optimal.

00:17:30.560 --> 00:17:34.880 align:middle line:84%
But it's also true that any
Pareto-optimal allocation

00:17:34.880 --> 00:17:37.160 align:middle line:84%
can be supported as
a price equilibrium

00:17:37.160 --> 00:17:40.040 align:middle line:84%
with transfers, as
in this definition.

00:17:40.040 --> 00:17:43.010 align:middle line:84%
However, to achieve the
fact that any optimum can

00:17:43.010 --> 00:17:45.980 align:middle line:84%
be supported, it's
kind of intuitive.

00:17:45.980 --> 00:17:49.570 align:middle line:84%
We may have to
redistribute wealth.

00:17:49.570 --> 00:17:53.110 align:middle line:84%
And again, I have a series
of lectures on this.

00:17:53.110 --> 00:17:55.780 align:middle line:84%
But if we're back in
the Edgeworth Box,

00:17:55.780 --> 00:17:57.850 align:middle line:84%
the competitive
equilibrium has picked

00:17:57.850 --> 00:18:01.480 align:middle line:84%
out one particular
Pareto-optimal allocation.

00:18:01.480 --> 00:18:05.530 align:middle line:84%
But as there are many
optimal allocations--

00:18:05.530 --> 00:18:07.300 align:middle line:84%
and to get to those,
we're going to have

00:18:07.300 --> 00:18:10.600 align:middle line:84%
to move this budget
line up or down, hence,

00:18:10.600 --> 00:18:11.815 align:middle line:90%
redistributing the wealth.

00:18:11.815 --> 00:18:14.550 align:middle line:90%


00:18:14.550 --> 00:18:18.510 align:middle line:84%
OK, so now that we've got
the concept of the Walrasian

00:18:18.510 --> 00:18:21.000 align:middle line:84%
equilibrium in hand,
I want to focus

00:18:21.000 --> 00:18:24.600 align:middle line:84%
on the primary application
today, which is production

00:18:24.600 --> 00:18:27.000 align:middle line:90%
in a small open economy.

00:18:27.000 --> 00:18:29.610 align:middle line:84%
We have to shift gears
just a little bit.

00:18:29.610 --> 00:18:32.250 align:middle line:84%
It's definitely going to
be general equilibrium.

00:18:32.250 --> 00:18:34.290 align:middle line:90%
We're going to have J firms.

00:18:34.290 --> 00:18:36.660 align:middle line:90%
And firms are producing goods.

00:18:36.660 --> 00:18:40.140 align:middle line:84%
So they're J goods
because we have J firms.

00:18:40.140 --> 00:18:42.450 align:middle line:90%
Firm J produces good, qJ.

00:18:42.450 --> 00:18:44.910 align:middle line:84%
And there are L
factors of production,

00:18:44.910 --> 00:18:49.080 align:middle line:84%
labeled, in this
case, Z. So Z1J is

00:18:49.080 --> 00:18:53.500 align:middle line:84%
the input of the first
factor by firm, J, and so on.

00:18:53.500 --> 00:18:57.450 align:middle line:84%
And each firm, J, has a strictly
concave production function,

00:18:57.450 --> 00:19:02.520 align:middle line:84%
indicated here by f sub J.
Output of consumer good, qJ,

00:19:02.520 --> 00:19:05.700 align:middle line:84%
is a function of the
input vector, ZJ.

00:19:05.700 --> 00:19:08.520 align:middle line:90%
So now we specify endowments.

00:19:08.520 --> 00:19:13.320 align:middle line:84%
The endowments are going to
be given of the factor inputs.

00:19:13.320 --> 00:19:15.060 align:middle line:90%
They're owned by households.

00:19:15.060 --> 00:19:17.670 align:middle line:84%
And for the sake of
argument, let's say they're

00:19:17.670 --> 00:19:19.110 align:middle line:90%
supplied in-elastically.

00:19:19.110 --> 00:19:21.340 align:middle line:84%
And they're not
going to be consumed.

00:19:21.340 --> 00:19:25.290 align:middle line:84%
What we're going to try to
do is find the factor prices

00:19:25.290 --> 00:19:27.630 align:middle line:84%
that's consistent
with an equilibrium

00:19:27.630 --> 00:19:29.980 align:middle line:90%
within this small open economy.

00:19:29.980 --> 00:19:34.150 align:middle line:84%
However, we're going to take the
prices of the goods as fixed.

00:19:34.150 --> 00:19:36.660 align:middle line:84%
So in that sense, it's
still partial equilibrium.

00:19:36.660 --> 00:19:39.990 align:middle line:84%
Think of it as a village,
as a small open economy

00:19:39.990 --> 00:19:42.420 align:middle line:84%
or a country, that
is small relative

00:19:42.420 --> 00:19:47.190 align:middle line:84%
to the rest of the world so that
these price vectors are fixed.

00:19:47.190 --> 00:19:49.860 align:middle line:84%
They're not going to be
the focus of our attention.

00:19:49.860 --> 00:19:52.800 align:middle line:84%
We are going to,
however, try to find

00:19:52.800 --> 00:19:56.400 align:middle line:84%
the allocation of the inputs
across all the firms, how

00:19:56.400 --> 00:19:59.610 align:middle line:84%
those endowments of
factors get used,

00:19:59.610 --> 00:20:03.390 align:middle line:84%
as well as the Walrasian
equilibrium price vector.

00:20:03.390 --> 00:20:09.840 align:middle line:84%
So firm j producing good qj
will maximize the difference

00:20:09.840 --> 00:20:12.580 align:middle line:90%
between revenues and costs.

00:20:12.580 --> 00:20:17.010 align:middle line:84%
So if w star, say, is a
candidate equilibrium price

00:20:17.010 --> 00:20:21.720 align:middle line:84%
vector, the firm would
choose its input vectors, Zj,

00:20:21.720 --> 00:20:27.180 align:middle line:84%
to maximize revenue minus costs
at that guessed equilibrium

00:20:27.180 --> 00:20:29.610 align:middle line:90%
price vector, w star.

00:20:29.610 --> 00:20:34.650 align:middle line:84%
p is, again, a given-- pj,
the price of quantity, j,

00:20:34.650 --> 00:20:38.250 align:middle line:90%
is externally specified.

00:20:38.250 --> 00:20:44.620 align:middle line:84%
So Z star j is the solution to
firm j's maximization problem.

00:20:44.620 --> 00:20:46.770 align:middle line:84%
And if we're finding
an equilibrium,

00:20:46.770 --> 00:20:49.530 align:middle line:84%
each firm will be
maximizing profits

00:20:49.530 --> 00:20:52.290 align:middle line:84%
and the sum of
the input demands,

00:20:52.290 --> 00:20:56.610 align:middle line:84%
in this case, the demand for
the L-th input from firm,

00:20:56.610 --> 00:20:59.670 align:middle line:84%
j, summing over all the
firms j, and in particular

00:20:59.670 --> 00:21:02.940 align:middle line:84%
the stars, which are
already profit-maximizing,

00:21:02.940 --> 00:21:07.980 align:middle line:84%
add up to the economy's
endowment of the factor, Z bar,

00:21:07.980 --> 00:21:09.570 align:middle line:90%
for the L-th factor.

00:21:09.570 --> 00:21:12.630 align:middle line:84%
And this is true for all,
each and every, factor,

00:21:12.630 --> 00:21:16.800 align:middle line:84%
L. This one is true for
each and every firm, j.

00:21:16.800 --> 00:21:20.610 align:middle line:84%
So this is what we're looking
for, the Walrasian equilibrium

00:21:20.610 --> 00:21:24.870 align:middle line:84%
in the factor markets, taking
external prices as given.

00:21:24.870 --> 00:21:28.560 align:middle line:84%
All right, you already know
something about the solutions

00:21:28.560 --> 00:21:31.140 align:middle line:84%
to the profit
maximization problem.

00:21:31.140 --> 00:21:34.620 align:middle line:84%
Namely, the value of
the marginal product

00:21:34.620 --> 00:21:37.920 align:middle line:84%
should be equal to--
of the L factor,

00:21:37.920 --> 00:21:39.900 align:middle line:90%
should be equal to its cost.

00:21:39.900 --> 00:21:43.800 align:middle line:84%
Just differentiate this
thing on the previous slide.

00:21:43.800 --> 00:21:47.700 align:middle line:84%
With respect to zj, you'll get
a derivative in the F function,

00:21:47.700 --> 00:21:52.830 align:middle line:84%
and will get the factor
input price on the cost side.

00:21:52.830 --> 00:21:53.910 align:middle line:90%
That's what this says.

00:21:53.910 --> 00:21:57.450 align:middle line:84%
Factor input price--
here's the derivative of F,

00:21:57.450 --> 00:21:59.100 align:middle line:90%
with respect to the L factor.

00:21:59.100 --> 00:22:03.540 align:middle line:84%
And that p is, of course, part
of the exogenously-given price

00:22:03.540 --> 00:22:04.530 align:middle line:90%
vector.

00:22:04.530 --> 00:22:07.990 align:middle line:84%
How many equations
are there like this?

00:22:07.990 --> 00:22:11.070 align:middle line:90%
Well, we have to specify here.

00:22:11.070 --> 00:22:12.870 align:middle line:90%
It's the L factor.

00:22:12.870 --> 00:22:15.150 align:middle line:90%
And we have L--

00:22:15.150 --> 00:22:17.520 align:middle line:90%
capital L factors all together.

00:22:17.520 --> 00:22:20.130 align:middle line:90%
And this is for the j firm.

00:22:20.130 --> 00:22:23.680 align:middle line:90%
But we have capital J firms.

00:22:23.680 --> 00:22:28.620 align:middle line:84%
So we have L times
J equations here.

00:22:28.620 --> 00:22:30.480 align:middle line:84%
And we have another
set of equations

00:22:30.480 --> 00:22:33.930 align:middle line:84%
which are the equilibrium,
that the demand for the factors

00:22:33.930 --> 00:22:35.370 align:middle line:90%
adds up to the total.

00:22:35.370 --> 00:22:38.710 align:middle line:84%
But again, this is true for
each and every L-th factor.

00:22:38.710 --> 00:22:40.810 align:middle line:90%
So there are L of these guys.

00:22:40.810 --> 00:22:44.490 align:middle line:84%
So we have L times
J equations here.

00:22:44.490 --> 00:22:47.650 align:middle line:90%
And we have L equations here.

00:22:47.650 --> 00:22:50.850 align:middle line:84%
So the number of equations
is equal to the number

00:22:50.850 --> 00:22:52.240 align:middle line:90%
of variables.

00:22:52.240 --> 00:22:54.330 align:middle line:84%
So in principle, we
should be able to solve

00:22:54.330 --> 00:22:57.420 align:middle line:84%
this system of equations to
determine the equilibrium

00:22:57.420 --> 00:22:58.890 align:middle line:90%
factor prices.

00:22:58.890 --> 00:23:01.100 align:middle line:84%
It's tedious and
boring to keep counting

00:23:01.100 --> 00:23:02.100 align:middle line:90%
the number of variables.

00:23:02.100 --> 00:23:06.720 align:middle line:84%
But it is actually useful to
see if we have fully specified,

00:23:06.720 --> 00:23:09.340 align:middle line:84%
and we potentially
have a solution.

00:23:09.340 --> 00:23:13.080 align:middle line:84%
So now, we've already
solved in lecture 4,

00:23:13.080 --> 00:23:17.020 align:middle line:84%
which was about production,
a cost minimization problem.

00:23:17.020 --> 00:23:21.030 align:middle line:84%
So we defined there
the cost for firm J

00:23:21.030 --> 00:23:27.120 align:middle line:84%
of producing the quantity, qj,
when the input vector was w.

00:23:27.120 --> 00:23:30.420 align:middle line:84%
I must say, even I
went back this morning

00:23:30.420 --> 00:23:33.540 align:middle line:84%
