00:25:47.730 --> 00:25:49.590 align:middle line:84%
Production functions,
just to write out

00:25:49.590 --> 00:25:54.060 align:middle line:84%
the notation, production
function for good 1, as it

00:25:54.060 --> 00:25:58.260 align:middle line:84%
inputs, the second
subscript denotes the firm,

00:25:58.260 --> 00:25:59.650 align:middle line:90%
the first one, the input.

00:25:59.650 --> 00:26:02.040 align:middle line:84%
So this is the first
input in firm 1,

00:26:02.040 --> 00:26:04.635 align:middle line:90%
the second input in firm 1.

00:26:04.635 --> 00:26:07.860 align:middle line:84%
f2 is output of
firm 2 as a function

00:26:07.860 --> 00:26:10.050 align:middle line:84%
of the first input
in for firm 2,

00:26:10.050 --> 00:26:12.420 align:middle line:90%
and the second input for firm 2.

00:26:12.420 --> 00:26:14.460 align:middle line:84%
And we're going to
assume, in this special 2

00:26:14.460 --> 00:26:17.400 align:middle line:84%
by 2 model, that these
production functions, each

00:26:17.400 --> 00:26:20.260 align:middle line:84%
of them, are constant
returns to scale.

00:26:20.260 --> 00:26:22.980 align:middle line:90%
So it's homogeneity of degree 1.

00:26:22.980 --> 00:26:26.370 align:middle line:84%
So if we're given a
vector of input prices

00:26:26.370 --> 00:26:29.670 align:middle line:84%
for capital and
labor, we can define

00:26:29.670 --> 00:26:34.320 align:middle line:84%
the cost of producing
one unit of good, j.

00:26:34.320 --> 00:26:38.010 align:middle line:90%
This is called the unit cost--

00:26:38.010 --> 00:26:42.630 align:middle line:84%
or you may want to review that
the cost of producing arbitrary

00:26:42.630 --> 00:26:45.420 align:middle line:84%
levels just scales
up or down depending

00:26:45.420 --> 00:26:48.120 align:middle line:84%
on whether that
other target level is

00:26:48.120 --> 00:26:50.400 align:middle line:90%
higher or lower than 1.

00:26:50.400 --> 00:26:53.910 align:middle line:84%
So once we have the cost
of producing one unit,

00:26:53.910 --> 00:26:57.330 align:middle line:84%
we can get the cost of
producing any number of units.

00:26:57.330 --> 00:27:00.840 align:middle line:84%
And what inputs solve
that minimum cost problem?

00:27:00.840 --> 00:27:02.940 align:middle line:90%
They're denoted with a's.

00:27:02.940 --> 00:27:07.890 align:middle line:84%
So for firm j, a1j
and a2j are the way

00:27:07.890 --> 00:27:12.600 align:middle line:84%
to achieve the least cost
when the input vector is w.

00:27:12.600 --> 00:27:17.190 align:middle line:84%
Input price vector
is w So here I

00:27:17.190 --> 00:27:20.350 align:middle line:84%
belabor a little bit
what you've seen before.

00:27:20.350 --> 00:27:22.540 align:middle line:90%
It's constant returns to scale.

00:27:22.540 --> 00:27:25.180 align:middle line:90%
So the cost function is linear.

00:27:25.180 --> 00:27:27.630 align:middle line:84%
Constant returns to scale
is this linear production

00:27:27.630 --> 00:27:29.220 align:middle line:90%
possibilities frontier.

00:27:29.220 --> 00:27:30.730 align:middle line:90%
Cost function is linear.

00:27:30.730 --> 00:27:32.790 align:middle line:84%
Marginal cost
equals average cost.

00:27:32.790 --> 00:27:35.070 align:middle line:84%
If price of a good,
say good j, is

00:27:35.070 --> 00:27:38.560 align:middle line:84%
less than marginal and average
cost, nothing gets produced.

00:27:38.560 --> 00:27:41.940 align:middle line:84%
And when price is equal to
marginal and average cost,

00:27:41.940 --> 00:27:43.620 align:middle line:84%
then they're happy
to produce anything.

00:27:43.620 --> 00:27:44.850 align:middle line:90%
Although profits are 0.

00:27:44.850 --> 00:27:48.930 align:middle line:84%
And price cannot be higher
because they would go bananas.

00:27:48.930 --> 00:27:52.170 align:middle line:84%
And then the assertion, which
I've already said twice,

00:27:52.170 --> 00:27:53.850 align:middle line:90%
profits must be zero.

00:27:53.850 --> 00:27:56.860 align:middle line:84%
And that's just, again, a
review slide from before.

00:27:56.860 --> 00:27:59.610 align:middle line:90%
So price equals cost.

00:27:59.610 --> 00:28:01.050 align:middle line:90%
This is the unit cost.

00:28:01.050 --> 00:28:03.000 align:middle line:90%
Price is the price of a unit.

00:28:03.000 --> 00:28:06.030 align:middle line:90%
So we have cost equal to prices.

00:28:06.030 --> 00:28:08.880 align:middle line:90%
OK, so another review.

00:28:08.880 --> 00:28:10.500 align:middle line:90%
We did this before, too.

00:28:10.500 --> 00:28:12.450 align:middle line:84%
What's special about
constant returns

00:28:12.450 --> 00:28:17.620 align:middle line:84%
to scale is we can solve
the problem for the one

00:28:17.620 --> 00:28:20.590 align:middle line:84%
unit of output,
minimize the cost

00:28:20.590 --> 00:28:23.110 align:middle line:90%
of achieving one unit of output.

00:28:23.110 --> 00:28:24.790 align:middle line:90%
And that's going to give us--

00:28:24.790 --> 00:28:26.710 align:middle line:84%
I guess I just
said this, the cost

00:28:26.710 --> 00:28:30.490 align:middle line:84%
for any other level of output,
just by scaling up and down

00:28:30.490 --> 00:28:31.420 align:middle line:90%
the solution.

00:28:31.420 --> 00:28:35.740 align:middle line:84%
And the ratios of input
use will not be changing.

00:28:35.740 --> 00:28:38.440 align:middle line:84%
I think in the previous
lecture, I actually

00:28:38.440 --> 00:28:41.110 align:middle line:84%
said I wasn't terribly
pleased with how

00:28:41.110 --> 00:28:42.700 align:middle line:90%
cryptically-worded it was.

00:28:42.700 --> 00:28:45.850 align:middle line:84%
And I gave you as an
informal homework assignment

00:28:45.850 --> 00:28:50.770 align:middle line:84%
to do a proof by contradiction
to prove that the input use

00:28:50.770 --> 00:28:53.590 align:middle line:84%
ratio is going to
be entirely dictated

00:28:53.590 --> 00:28:57.790 align:middle line:84%
by the input prices,
regardless of the scale.

00:28:57.790 --> 00:29:01.150 align:middle line:84%
That is to say, this input
ratio will remain constant.

00:29:01.150 --> 00:29:04.960 align:middle line:84%
And again, please, I apologize
because I'm throwing at you

00:29:04.960 --> 00:29:06.580 align:middle line:90%
things from a previous lecture.

00:29:06.580 --> 00:29:07.570 align:middle line:90%
It was lecture 4.

00:29:07.570 --> 00:29:09.370 align:middle line:90%
So that was some time ago.

00:29:09.370 --> 00:29:10.870 align:middle line:84%
But I don't want
to belabor it today

00:29:10.870 --> 00:29:12.740 align:middle line:84%
or we won't get
to something new.

00:29:12.740 --> 00:29:15.940 align:middle line:84%
So for now, we'll just
accept this as a fact.

00:29:15.940 --> 00:29:19.600 align:middle line:84%
Then we come to a key definition
about factor intensity.

00:29:19.600 --> 00:29:25.180 align:middle line:84%
Say good 1 is more intensive
in factor 1 than good 2.

00:29:25.180 --> 00:29:27.940 align:middle line:84%
Then the production of
good 2, if naturally,

00:29:27.940 --> 00:29:33.340 align:middle line:84%
firm producing good 1 uses
relatively more of input 1--

00:29:33.340 --> 00:29:37.600 align:middle line:84%
input 1 relative to input
2, then does firm 2.

00:29:37.600 --> 00:29:41.200 align:middle line:84%
So the definition, to say
good 1 is relatively more

00:29:41.200 --> 00:29:44.950 align:middle line:84%
intensive than factor 1, means
that the ratio of factor 1

00:29:44.950 --> 00:29:49.150 align:middle line:84%
to factor 2 in firm 1 is
higher than it is in firm 2.

00:29:49.150 --> 00:29:51.640 align:middle line:84%
So it's a pretty
natural definition.

00:29:51.640 --> 00:29:53.620 align:middle line:90%
Of course, it can move around.

00:29:53.620 --> 00:29:57.080 align:middle line:84%
But the inequality
remains the same.

00:29:57.080 --> 00:29:57.880 align:middle line:90%
It's intense.

00:29:57.880 --> 00:30:01.510 align:middle line:84%
No matter what the
input price ratio is,

00:30:01.510 --> 00:30:04.960 align:middle line:84%
the optimizing choice
of inputs will always

00:30:04.960 --> 00:30:09.610 align:middle line:84%
satisfy this inequality when
comparing firm 1 to firm 2.

00:30:09.610 --> 00:30:13.840 align:middle line:84%
So now something a bit new
that was not in lecture 4,

00:30:13.840 --> 00:30:15.340 align:middle line:90%
although it's not hard.

00:30:15.340 --> 00:30:20.770 align:middle line:84%
We're going to plot the cost of
producing one unit of a good.

00:30:20.770 --> 00:30:23.770 align:middle line:84%
We're going to plot that
cost curve as a function

00:30:23.770 --> 00:30:27.670 align:middle line:90%
of the input prices, w1 and w2.

00:30:27.670 --> 00:30:32.380 align:middle line:84%
So in particular, if, say,
for a given w1 and w2 bar,

00:30:32.380 --> 00:30:35.650 align:middle line:84%
your assertion is we're
on this cost curve,

00:30:35.650 --> 00:30:41.560 align:middle line:84%
then if we increase the price
of the first input to w prime 1

00:30:41.560 --> 00:30:44.050 align:middle line:84%
and we're supposed
to be on an isocost,

00:30:44.050 --> 00:30:46.480 align:middle line:84%
meaning same cost
curve, the increase

00:30:46.480 --> 00:30:50.000 align:middle line:84%
in the first factor price would
mean the cost would be higher.

00:30:50.000 --> 00:30:53.530 align:middle line:84%
So we have to lower the
price of the second factor

00:30:53.530 --> 00:30:55.310 align:middle line:90%
in order to compensate.

00:30:55.310 --> 00:30:58.960 align:middle line:84%
So that on net, after
we make this move,

00:30:58.960 --> 00:31:02.780 align:middle line:84%
total costs are the same
because it is the isocost curve.

00:31:02.780 --> 00:31:07.090 align:middle line:84%
So this down-sloping nature
of the isocost curve,

00:31:07.090 --> 00:31:11.570 align:middle line:84%
plotted against various input
prices, makes a lot of sense.

00:31:11.570 --> 00:31:14.260 align:middle line:84%
The other thing is
this concave shape.

00:31:14.260 --> 00:31:19.060 align:middle line:84%
This comes from a property
of the minimized cost.

00:31:19.060 --> 00:31:24.190 align:middle line:84%
In particular, this set of input
prices at or above the cost

00:31:24.190 --> 00:31:25.780 align:middle line:90%
line is a convex set.

00:31:25.780 --> 00:31:27.730 align:middle line:84%
But we did this a
lot with respect

00:31:27.730 --> 00:31:30.550 align:middle line:84%
to the consumer
optimization problem.

00:31:30.550 --> 00:31:34.390 align:middle line:84%
We defined quasi-concave utility
functions and the associated

00:31:34.390 --> 00:31:35.920 align:middle line:90%
concave indifference curves.

00:31:35.920 --> 00:31:37.960 align:middle line:84%
And we had the
weak upper contour

00:31:37.960 --> 00:31:40.090 align:middle line:90%
set as being strictly convex.

00:31:40.090 --> 00:31:41.650 align:middle line:90%
So these are analogs here.

00:31:41.650 --> 00:31:45.310 align:middle line:84%
Now, the assertion is that
this cost function is, in fact,

00:31:45.310 --> 00:31:46.330 align:middle line:90%
concave.

00:31:46.330 --> 00:31:48.850 align:middle line:90%
And again, as a review--

00:31:48.850 --> 00:31:50.850 align:middle line:90%
but who remembers?

00:31:50.850 --> 00:31:54.540 align:middle line:84%
We already had
derived in lecture 4

00:31:54.540 --> 00:31:58.030 align:middle line:84%
that the cost function is
concave in the input prices.

00:31:58.030 --> 00:32:01.140 align:middle line:84%
So I just pasted in
the slide to remind us.

00:32:01.140 --> 00:32:04.170 align:middle line:84%
So now we have
down-sloping concave.

00:32:04.170 --> 00:32:05.880 align:middle line:84%
And the other thing
that's going on here

00:32:05.880 --> 00:32:09.330 align:middle line:84%
is, at these particular
input prices,

00:32:09.330 --> 00:32:11.310 align:middle line:84%
if we go back to
Shephard's lemma,

00:32:11.310 --> 00:32:14.580 align:middle line:84%
the derivative of
the minimized cost,

00:32:14.580 --> 00:32:17.760 align:middle line:84%
with respect to, say, the
price of the first factor,

00:32:17.760 --> 00:32:20.790 align:middle line:84%
is the level input
of the first factor,

00:32:20.790 --> 00:32:24.040 align:middle line:84%
and similarly, for the level
input of the second factor.

00:32:24.040 --> 00:32:27.480 align:middle line:84%
So the ratio, the slope
of this line, which

00:32:27.480 --> 00:32:29.850 align:middle line:84%
is the ratio of the
derivatives of the cost

00:32:29.850 --> 00:32:33.630 align:middle line:84%
curve at an optimum,
must, by Shephard's lemma,

00:32:33.630 --> 00:32:37.630 align:middle line:84%
be equal to the ratio of
the optimizing inputs.

00:32:37.630 --> 00:32:42.870 align:middle line:84%
And again, logically, if you
increased the input price

00:32:42.870 --> 00:32:46.470 align:middle line:84%
of factor 1, keeping
cost constant,

00:32:46.470 --> 00:32:49.170 align:middle line:84%
you would move along
this isocost line.

00:32:49.170 --> 00:32:53.100 align:middle line:84%
And you would increase
the amount of good 2

00:32:53.100 --> 00:32:57.870 align:middle line:84%
and factor 2, and decrease
the amount of factor 1.

00:32:57.870 --> 00:32:59.700 align:middle line:84%
You substitute away
from the factor, which

00:32:59.700 --> 00:33:01.300 align:middle line:90%
has now increased in price.

00:33:01.300 --> 00:33:04.350 align:middle line:84%
So in the earlier slide, lecture
4, I didn't replicate it.

00:33:04.350 --> 00:33:09.420 align:middle line:84%
We had a Walt Disney example
about machinery versus humans.

00:33:09.420 --> 00:33:12.600 align:middle line:84%
Now I'll just warn
you, it is very hard

00:33:12.600 --> 00:33:14.790 align:middle line:84%
to remember what's
divided by what.

00:33:14.790 --> 00:33:18.300 align:middle line:84%
But anyway, the fact that this
perpendicular becomes steeper

00:33:18.300 --> 00:33:21.720 align:middle line:84%
is consistent with
the input of factor 1

00:33:21.720 --> 00:33:25.560 align:middle line:84%
going down because
