00:33:25.560 --> 00:33:28.330 align:middle line:90%
All right, did that.

00:33:28.330 --> 00:33:32.310 align:middle line:84%
So now, how do we solve for
equilibrium factor prices?

00:33:32.310 --> 00:33:35.100 align:middle line:84%
This is just a picture
of a particular firm

00:33:35.100 --> 00:33:37.380 align:middle line:90%
and what it would do, firm j--

00:33:37.380 --> 00:33:39.810 align:middle line:84%
what it would do as we
vary the input prices?

00:33:39.810 --> 00:33:42.210 align:middle line:84%
And we want to find
particular input prices,

00:33:42.210 --> 00:33:45.960 align:middle line:84%
such that both firms
are minimizing costs,

00:33:45.960 --> 00:33:48.390 align:middle line:84%
and all the factors
get utilized.

00:33:48.390 --> 00:33:51.810 align:middle line:84%
So remember, because we have
constant returns to scale

00:33:51.810 --> 00:33:55.050 align:middle line:84%
and because we've taken the
right hand side prices as

00:33:55.050 --> 00:33:57.990 align:middle line:84%
arbitrary and given,
coming from nowhere,

00:33:57.990 --> 00:34:01.800 align:middle line:84%
say, but certainly known
to the firms, as part

00:34:01.800 --> 00:34:04.770 align:middle line:84%
of the solution,
the unit cost has

00:34:04.770 --> 00:34:08.670 align:middle line:84%
to equal to the price
for both firms 1 and 2.

00:34:08.670 --> 00:34:13.330 align:middle line:84%
So we have, from this, two
equations and two unknowns,

00:34:13.330 --> 00:34:18.310 align:middle line:84%
namely the factor prices, w1 and
w2, that we want to solve for.

00:34:18.310 --> 00:34:23.280 align:middle line:84%
So visually, we can actually
put both firm 1's and firm 2's

00:34:23.280 --> 00:34:26.219 align:middle line:84%
isocost lines on
the same diagram.

00:34:26.219 --> 00:34:28.150 align:middle line:84%
In other words,
I've gone from here,

00:34:28.150 --> 00:34:34.050 align:middle line:84%
which was firm j, and firm
j's particular isocost line--

00:34:34.050 --> 00:34:36.870 align:middle line:84%
talking about how it
varies with w1 and w2,

00:34:36.870 --> 00:34:40.260 align:middle line:84%
to this diagram, in which
we have not only firm 1--

00:34:40.260 --> 00:34:43.320 align:middle line:90%
excuse me, but also firm two.

00:34:43.320 --> 00:34:46.469 align:middle line:84%
And if we're going to
find an equilibrium,

00:34:46.469 --> 00:34:50.310 align:middle line:84%
we're going to find price for
factor 1 and a price for factor

00:34:50.310 --> 00:34:51.540 align:middle line:90%
2, each.

00:34:51.540 --> 00:34:54.150 align:middle line:84%
So each firm, in an
equilibrium, is going

00:34:54.150 --> 00:34:56.670 align:middle line:90%
to face the same factor prices.

00:34:56.670 --> 00:35:00.810 align:middle line:84%
And each firm must lie
on its own unit cost

00:35:00.810 --> 00:35:03.940 align:middle line:84%
curve equal to the price
from this equation.

00:35:03.940 --> 00:35:10.110 align:middle line:84%
So you can see the unit cost
for firm 1 equal to p 2,

00:35:10.110 --> 00:35:12.930 align:middle line:84%
the unit cost of
firm 2 equal to p2.

00:35:12.930 --> 00:35:16.230 align:middle line:84%
These are particular
isocost curves for firm 1

00:35:16.230 --> 00:35:19.920 align:middle line:84%
and firm 2 that are associated
with two of the equilibrium

00:35:19.920 --> 00:35:20.710 align:middle line:90%
equations.

00:35:20.710 --> 00:35:23.580 align:middle line:84%
And if we're going to find
common factor prices faced

00:35:23.580 --> 00:35:26.340 align:middle line:84%
by both of the
firms, we only want

00:35:26.340 --> 00:35:28.890 align:middle line:84%
one factor price for
the first factor,

00:35:28.890 --> 00:35:31.150 align:middle line:84%
and one factor price
for the second one.

00:35:31.150 --> 00:35:33.240 align:middle line:84%
So where can that
happen in this diagram?

00:35:33.240 --> 00:35:38.110 align:middle line:84%
Only one spot, and that's where
these isocost curves cross.

00:35:38.110 --> 00:35:40.930 align:middle line:84%
So this is kind of
displaying the equilibrium.

00:35:40.930 --> 00:35:45.270 align:middle line:84%
Let me say one more word about
why they're shaped in this way.

00:35:45.270 --> 00:35:49.080 align:middle line:84%
Remember, firm 1 is
intensive in factor 1.

00:35:49.080 --> 00:35:51.900 align:middle line:84%
So if we did move
along its curve,

00:35:51.900 --> 00:35:55.170 align:middle line:90%
lowering w2 and increasing w1--

00:35:55.170 --> 00:35:57.840 align:middle line:84%
because it's
intensive in factor 1,

00:35:57.840 --> 00:35:59.730 align:middle line:84%
it tends to use a
lot of factor 1.

00:35:59.730 --> 00:36:02.160 align:middle line:84%
So increasing the
price of factor 1

00:36:02.160 --> 00:36:04.740 align:middle line:84%
is kind over big
burden for firm 1.

00:36:04.740 --> 00:36:07.260 align:middle line:84%
And to compensate,
we have to lower

00:36:07.260 --> 00:36:10.140 align:middle line:84%
the price of the second
factor quite a lot,

00:36:10.140 --> 00:36:15.000 align:middle line:84%
relative to the compensation
we would have to offer firm 2.

00:36:15.000 --> 00:36:19.950 align:middle line:84%
For the same increase in w1,
the corresponding decrease in w2

00:36:19.950 --> 00:36:24.630 align:middle line:84%
is less for firm 2 than firm
1 because, again, firm 1

00:36:24.630 --> 00:36:26.790 align:middle line:90%
is intensive in factor 1.

00:36:26.790 --> 00:36:29.100 align:middle line:84%
So this factor
intensity, which I

00:36:29.100 --> 00:36:31.470 align:middle line:84%
said was a very
natural definition,

00:36:31.470 --> 00:36:34.860 align:middle line:84%
is true everywhere
by definition.

00:36:34.860 --> 00:36:38.730 align:middle line:84%
Hence, the curve for firm 1
has to be steeper everywhere

00:36:38.730 --> 00:36:40.350 align:middle line:90%
than the curve for firm 2.

00:36:40.350 --> 00:36:42.900 align:middle line:84%
And that's why
they have to cross.

00:36:42.900 --> 00:36:45.150 align:middle line:90%
Questions?

00:36:45.150 --> 00:36:48.370 align:middle line:84%
OK, so again, just
to review this slide,

00:36:48.370 --> 00:36:50.130 align:middle line:84%
we're looking for
an equilibrium.

00:36:50.130 --> 00:36:53.160 align:middle line:84%
The claim is we found
it now because we

00:36:53.160 --> 00:36:57.480 align:middle line:84%
have found the factor prices
for the first and second factor,

00:36:57.480 --> 00:37:01.530 align:middle line:84%
such that each firm is
minimizing its unit costs

00:37:01.530 --> 00:37:03.870 align:middle line:90%
associated with the cost--

00:37:03.870 --> 00:37:06.590 align:middle line:84%
the unit cost being
equal to price.

00:37:06.590 --> 00:37:09.460 align:middle line:84%
So these must be the
equilibrium quantities

00:37:09.460 --> 00:37:13.930 align:middle line:84%
of the factors being utilized
in each of the two firms.

00:37:13.930 --> 00:37:18.430 align:middle line:84%
All right, so we're kind
of doing an algorithm here.

00:37:18.430 --> 00:37:23.530 align:middle line:84%
The algorithm was define
Walrasian equilibrium.

00:37:23.530 --> 00:37:26.650 align:middle line:84%
And do that for
this 2 by 2 model.

00:37:26.650 --> 00:37:29.500 align:middle line:84%
And without telling you
that I was going to do this,

00:37:29.500 --> 00:37:31.420 align:middle line:90%
we're doing it iteratively.

00:37:31.420 --> 00:37:36.400 align:middle line:84%
The very first thing we do is
solve for the factor prices.

00:37:36.400 --> 00:37:39.620 align:middle line:84%
And now we're going to get
the quantities this way.

00:37:39.620 --> 00:37:41.470 align:middle line:84%
So the quantities,
naturally, are

00:37:41.470 --> 00:37:45.160 align:middle line:84%
going to come from a diagram
where we have isoquants.

00:37:45.160 --> 00:37:47.350 align:middle line:84%
So here we have the
input of factor 1,

00:37:47.350 --> 00:37:48.850 align:middle line:90%
the input of factor 2.

00:37:48.850 --> 00:37:52.270 align:middle line:84%
For firm j, this is an
isoquant equal production,

00:37:52.270 --> 00:37:55.340 align:middle line:84%
as you move along
that isoquant curve.

00:37:55.340 --> 00:37:58.660 align:middle line:84%
And again, you may
remember, or not,

00:37:58.660 --> 00:38:04.900 align:middle line:84%
that to minimize the cost
of producing one unit,

00:38:04.900 --> 00:38:08.170 align:middle line:84%
we find the tangency,
where the isoquant

00:38:08.170 --> 00:38:11.650 align:middle line:90%
is tangent to the isocost line.

00:38:11.650 --> 00:38:14.230 align:middle line:84%
Now again, it's a bit
dizzying because what's

00:38:14.230 --> 00:38:18.880 align:middle line:84%
an isocost line in one space
is a different-looking cost

00:38:18.880 --> 00:38:19.870 align:middle line:90%
line in another.

00:38:19.870 --> 00:38:22.150 align:middle line:84%
In this space,
the isocost curves

00:38:22.150 --> 00:38:25.300 align:middle line:90%
are concave, as I was saying.

00:38:25.300 --> 00:38:27.670 align:middle line:84%
That's in the space
of factor inputs.

00:38:27.670 --> 00:38:29.950 align:middle line:90%
W1 and W2 prices.

00:38:29.950 --> 00:38:34.210 align:middle line:84%
w1 and w2 here,
the isocost line is

00:38:34.210 --> 00:38:39.880 align:middle line:84%
linear, in the space of
input quantities, z1 and z2.

00:38:39.880 --> 00:38:44.470 align:middle line:84%
So again, the minimized cost
of producing one unit of output

00:38:44.470 --> 00:38:49.780 align:middle line:84%
here at these factor
prices, w, is this tangency.

00:38:49.780 --> 00:38:55.120 align:middle line:84%
And it's associated with the
inputs, a1 and a2, to firm, j.

00:38:55.120 --> 00:38:58.240 align:middle line:84%
And again, the
reason is something

00:38:58.240 --> 00:39:00.820 align:middle line:84%
we reviewed before,
that when you take

00:39:00.820 --> 00:39:07.510 align:middle line:84%
the derivative of the isoquant,
we're getting dz2, dz1,

00:39:07.510 --> 00:39:09.290 align:middle line:84%
the quantity is
staying the same.

00:39:09.290 --> 00:39:11.530 align:middle line:90%
So we solve for the solution.

00:39:11.530 --> 00:39:14.380 align:middle line:84%
And we're getting a relationship
between the derivative

00:39:14.380 --> 00:39:17.720 align:middle line:90%
of the isocost and the inputs.

00:39:17.720 --> 00:39:22.160 align:middle line:84%
OK, so now we want to solve,
not only for quantities,

00:39:22.160 --> 00:39:25.160 align:middle line:90%
but the equilibrium amounts.

00:39:25.160 --> 00:39:29.540 align:middle line:84%
Now remember, again, here
we were playing around

00:39:29.540 --> 00:39:30.980 align:middle line:90%
with unit costs.

00:39:30.980 --> 00:39:34.280 align:middle line:84%
But we don't know the level
of the quantities yet.

00:39:34.280 --> 00:39:38.270 align:middle line:84%
And likewise, hence, we don't
know the levels of the inputs.

00:39:38.270 --> 00:39:40.520 align:middle line:84%
Although we do know
something about the ratios

00:39:40.520 --> 00:39:45.260 align:middle line:84%
of the inputs one once we find
the equilibrium factor prices.

00:39:45.260 --> 00:39:47.990 align:middle line:84%
So having found the
equilibrium factor prices,

00:39:47.990 --> 00:39:51.950 align:middle line:84%
we now turn to
determining the inputs.

00:39:51.950 --> 00:39:54.470 align:middle line:84%
But it almost looks
like a review.

00:39:54.470 --> 00:39:57.740 align:middle line:84%
The input ratio
for firm 1 must be

00:39:57.740 --> 00:40:01.370 align:middle line:84%
those a coefficients,
the solution to the cost

00:40:01.370 --> 00:40:03.800 align:middle line:84%
minimization problem
in the quantity

00:40:03.800 --> 00:40:08.270 align:middle line:84%
space at the equilibrium
factor prices, w star.

00:40:08.270 --> 00:40:09.560 align:middle line:90%
This is true for firm 1.

00:40:09.560 --> 00:40:11.490 align:middle line:90%
It's also true for firm 2.

00:40:11.490 --> 00:40:14.540 align:middle line:84%
So the ratios of
inputs being used

00:40:14.540 --> 00:40:17.990 align:middle line:84%
must be consistent with
the optimized ratio

00:40:17.990 --> 00:40:21.890 align:middle line:84%
of inputs being used at the
equilibrium factor prices.

00:40:21.890 --> 00:40:23.360 align:middle line:90%
There are two equations there.

00:40:23.360 --> 00:40:27.890 align:middle line:84%
There's another equation,
namely that the inputs being

00:40:27.890 --> 00:40:31.460 align:middle line:84%
used by the firm, in this case,
input 1, and the second, input

00:40:31.460 --> 00:40:32.060 align:middle line:90%
2--

00:40:32.060 --> 00:40:34.790 align:middle line:84%
input 1 in firm 1,
input 1 in firm 2,

00:40:34.790 --> 00:40:37.470 align:middle line:84%
must sum up to the
aggregate endowments.

00:40:37.470 --> 00:40:41.690 align:middle line:84%
So finally, another
ingredient of the economy,

00:40:41.690 --> 00:40:44.360 align:middle line:84%
the level of the
input endowments,

00:40:44.360 --> 00:40:46.500 align:middle line:90%
is here on the right hand side.

00:40:46.500 --> 00:40:49.640 align:middle line:84%
And when we found an
equilibrium in input use,

00:40:49.640 --> 00:40:53.730 align:middle line:84%
it has to satisfy this
system of equations.

00:40:53.730 --> 00:40:56.300 align:middle line:84%
Now I can show you
a picture of it.

00:40:56.300 --> 00:40:59.150 align:middle line:84%
You may remember that
when we did production,

00:40:59.150 --> 00:41:01.650 align:middle line:84%
we talked about the
production box--

00:41:01.650 --> 00:41:04.700 align:middle line:84%
not the Edgeworth Box
of the consumer theory,

00:41:04.700 --> 00:41:08.030 align:middle line:84%
but the production box
of production theory.

00:41:08.030 --> 00:41:10.610 align:middle line:84%
We had, again,
like the isoquants,

00:41:10.610 --> 00:41:13.940 align:middle line:84%
input 1 and input 2
on the x and y-axis,

00:41:13.940 --> 00:41:17.270 align:middle line:90%
firm 1 is oriented around 01.

00:41:17.270 --> 00:41:20.360 align:middle line:84%
And we have
isoquants for firm 1.

00:41:20.360 --> 00:41:24.080 align:middle line:84%
And this ratio, the
slope of this line,

00:41:24.080 --> 00:41:27.720 align:middle line:84%
is the optimizing
ratio of inputs.

00:41:27.720 --> 00:41:30.770 align:middle line:84%
And again, that
optimizing ratio of inputs

00:41:30.770 --> 00:41:33.410 align:middle line:84%
is entirely pinned down
by the equilibrium factor

00:41:33.410 --> 00:41:35.400 align:middle line:90%
prices, which we already found.

00:41:35.400 --> 00:41:38.600 align:middle line:84%
So they have to lie on
this line somewhere.

00:41:38.600 --> 00:41:39.710 align:middle line:90%
Why here?

00:41:39.710 --> 00:41:44.030 align:middle line:84%
Because when we go up to firm
2, the same thing is true,

00:41:44.030 --> 00:41:49.040 align:middle line:84%
that the optimizing input ratio
of factor 2 to factor 1 must

00:41:49.040 --> 00:41:53.550 align:middle line:84%
lie on this line coming
out of the 02 origin.

00:41:53.550 --> 00:41:56.810 align:middle line:84%
So input ratio for
firm 1 is fixed.

00:41:56.810 --> 00:41:59.347 align:middle line:90%
Input ratio for firm 2 is fixed.

00:41:59.347 --> 00:41:59.930 align:middle line:90%
Fixed at what?

00:41:59.930 --> 00:42:03.410 align:middle line:84%
Fixed at these levels, as
in the earlier diagrams.

00:42:03.410 --> 00:42:07.430 align:middle line:84%
Hence, in an equilibrium, to be
consistent with each of them,

00:42:07.430 --> 00:42:10.190 align:middle line:84%
it must be where
these lines cross.

00:42:10.190 --> 00:42:12.650 align:middle line:84%
So this finally
determines output

00:42:12.650 --> 00:42:14.840 align:middle line:90%
because we have isoquants here.

00:42:14.840 --> 00:42:18.500 align:middle line:84%
So firm 1 is producing
on this isoquant.

00:42:18.500 --> 00:42:20.870 align:middle line:84%
Firm 2 is producing
on this isoquant.

00:42:20.870 --> 00:42:24.200 align:middle line:84%
So now we've got
both, the equilibrium

00:42:24.200 --> 00:42:26.240 align:middle line:90%
level of the inputs--

00:42:26.240 --> 00:42:29.210 align:middle line:84%
which is boom boom and
boom boom, as well as

00:42:29.210 --> 00:42:32.560 align:middle line:84%
the outputs associated
with these isoquants.

00:42:32.560 --> 00:42:36.830 align:middle line:90%
OK, are there questions so far?

00:42:36.830 --> 00:42:39.400 align:middle line:84%
Well, let me just
say, when you review,

00:42:39.400 --> 00:42:41.740 align:middle line:84%
there is a lot of
content in this lecture.

00:42:41.740 --> 00:42:45.130 align:middle line:84%
Some of it's review, as I've
already been apologizing.

00:42:45.130 --> 00:42:46.750 align:middle line:90%
Go back to lecture 4.

00:42:46.750 --> 00:42:49.120 align:middle line:84%
But also, it's kind of
stacked, in the sense

00:42:49.120 --> 00:42:53.770 align:middle line:84%
that each segment builds
on the subsequent segments.

00:42:53.770 --> 00:42:55.450 align:middle line:84%
And it's very hard
to take it in when

00:42:55.450 --> 00:42:58.100 align:middle line:84%
I go through these slides
for the first time.

00:42:58.100 --> 00:43:01.100 align:middle line:84%
But I think if you review
it the second round,

00:43:01.100 --> 00:43:03.820 align:middle line:84%
you'll see how the ingredients
are coming together.

00:43:03.820 --> 00:43:06.760 align:middle line:84%
Anyway, where are
we at this point?

00:43:06.760 --> 00:43:09.460 align:middle line:84%
We had a country,
say, an economy,

00:43:09.460 --> 00:43:12.970 align:middle line:84%
with two types of
firms, j, equal 1, 2.

00:43:12.970 --> 00:43:16.390 align:middle line:84%
We have two factors,
say labor and capital.

00:43:16.390 --> 00:43:20.740 align:middle line:84%
We had this economy facing
externally-given arbitrary

00:43:20.740 --> 00:43:25.330 align:middle line:84%
prices, p1 and p2,
for the firms 1 and 2.

00:43:25.330 --> 00:43:30.370 align:middle line:84%
And we have now solved for the
market clearing factor prices

00:43:30.370 --> 00:43:35.140 align:middle line:84%
in the input markets for the
level of the inputs being used

00:43:35.140 --> 00:43:38.510 align:middle line:84%
and the equilibrium
quantities being produced.

00:43:38.510 --> 00:43:40.560 align:middle line:90%
That's how far we got already.

00:43:40.560 --> 00:43:44.240 align:middle line:84%
OK, so now I want to
get to the trade part.

00:43:44.240 --> 00:43:45.920 align:middle line:84%
And I'm going to
add the other two.

00:43:45.920 --> 00:43:49.630 align:middle line:84%
So this is two firms, two
factors, and two countries.

00:43:49.630 --> 00:43:52.390 align:middle line:84%
And the two countries
are denoted A and B.

00:43:52.390 --> 00:43:56.260 align:middle line:84%
So each country has
the same technologies.

00:43:56.260 --> 00:43:59.350 align:middle line:84%
Each country can produce
good 1 and produce

00:43:59.350 --> 00:44:04.450 align:middle line:84%
good 2 with these factors, the
two factors, labor and capital.

00:44:04.450 --> 00:44:07.090 align:middle line:84%
We could have imagined
different technologies

00:44:07.090 --> 00:44:09.580 align:middle line:84%
in the different
countries, and in a minute,

00:44:09.580 --> 00:44:11.080 align:middle line:90%
different preferences.

00:44:11.080 --> 00:44:13.240 align:middle line:84%
You haven't seen the
consumer side of it yet.

00:44:13.240 --> 00:44:18.400 align:middle line:84%
But the famous 2 by 2 by 2
model with some amazingly cool

00:44:18.400 --> 00:44:21.430 align:middle line:84%
theorems assumes
identical technologies

00:44:21.430 --> 00:44:24.400 align:middle line:84%
and identical preferences
in the two countries.

00:44:24.400 --> 00:44:26.560 align:middle line:84%
What's different across
the two countries

00:44:26.560 --> 00:44:28.240 align:middle line:90%
are the factor endowments.

00:44:28.240 --> 00:44:31.000 align:middle line:84%
Namely, one country
is capital abundant.

00:44:31.000 --> 00:44:32.890 align:middle line:90%
The other is labor abundant.

00:44:32.890 --> 00:44:35.590 align:middle line:84%
So you might, for
example, have thought--

00:44:35.590 --> 00:44:37.660 align:middle line:84%
although this is
no longer as true

00:44:37.660 --> 00:44:40.420 align:middle line:84%
as it once was for reasons
of the theorem we're

00:44:40.420 --> 00:44:41.560 align:middle line:90%
about to see--

00:44:41.560 --> 00:44:45.040 align:middle line:84%
that countries like
Mexico or China

00:44:45.040 --> 00:44:47.530 align:middle line:84%
are relatively
well-endowed with labor.

00:44:47.530 --> 00:44:50.200 align:middle line:84%
The US, being quite
industrialized,

00:44:50.200 --> 00:44:53.230 align:middle line:84%
is relatively
well-endowed with capital.

00:44:53.230 --> 00:44:57.010 align:middle line:84%
So the US, as
distinct from Mexico,

00:44:57.010 --> 00:45:00.010 align:middle line:90%
is a capital-abundant country.

00:45:00.010 --> 00:45:02.830 align:middle line:84%
And Mexico is a
labor-abundant country.

00:45:02.830 --> 00:45:06.520 align:middle line:84%
I choose the example carefully
because, again, with NAFTA,

00:45:06.520 --> 00:45:08.530 align:middle line:84%
there's all kinds
of controversies

00:45:08.530 --> 00:45:12.640 align:middle line:84%
about what happened to the
wages of US domestic workers

00:45:12.640 --> 00:45:16.120 align:middle line:84%
when the US increased
its trade with Mexico.

00:45:16.120 --> 00:45:18.670 align:middle line:84%
We now have a theorem
that's going to tell us

00:45:18.670 --> 00:45:20.080 align:middle line:90%
something about that.

00:45:20.080 --> 00:45:23.470 align:middle line:84%
Oh, anyway, here, two countries,
A and B, with different factor

00:45:23.470 --> 00:45:25.780 align:middle line:84%
endowments-- one being
capital abundant,

00:45:25.780 --> 00:45:27.130 align:middle line:90%
and the other labor abundant.

00:45:27.130 --> 00:45:29.170 align:middle line:84%
Now, what if there's
no trade at all?

00:45:29.170 --> 00:45:30.580 align:middle line:90%
We're in autarky.

00:45:30.580 --> 00:45:34.180 align:middle line:84%
What's going to determine the
price of the consumption goods?

00:45:34.180 --> 00:45:36.580 align:middle line:84%
Well, that's where we
need the consumer part.

00:45:36.580 --> 00:45:38.740 align:middle line:84%
We're going to need the
representative consumer

00:45:38.740 --> 00:45:41.440 align:middle line:84%
in a given country
maximizing utility,

00:45:41.440 --> 00:45:46.580 align:middle line:84%
given its ownership of factors,
and potentially shares.

00:45:46.580 --> 00:45:49.120 align:middle line:84%
Although in this constant
returns to scale world,

00:45:49.120 --> 00:45:50.950 align:middle line:90%
there are no profits anyway.

00:45:50.950 --> 00:45:53.680 align:middle line:84%
So we have an entirely
domestic market,

00:45:53.680 --> 00:45:56.980 align:middle line:84%
like China completely closed
to the rest of the world.

00:45:56.980 --> 00:46:00.010 align:middle line:84%
Now we jump all the
way to free trade.

00:46:00.010 --> 00:46:02.410 align:middle line:84%
And if there's no cost
of shipping goods around,

00:46:02.410 --> 00:46:03.640 align:middle line:90%
there's an abstraction.

00:46:03.640 --> 00:46:05.320 align:middle line:84%
The price of the
two goods now have

00:46:05.320 --> 00:46:09.400 align:middle line:84%
to be the same in each
country because if there's

00:46:09.400 --> 00:46:13.180 align:middle line:84%
no cost to shipping goods
around, if the price of a good

00:46:13.180 --> 00:46:17.830 align:middle line:84%
were lower in one country
than another, then

00:46:17.830 --> 00:46:20.290 align:middle line:84%
they would basically
be exporting

00:46:20.290 --> 00:46:22.270 align:middle line:84%
a lot of that good
at a low price

00:46:22.270 --> 00:46:24.430 align:middle line:84%
to the other country
that's willing to buy it

00:46:24.430 --> 00:46:25.340 align:middle line:90%
at a high price.

00:46:25.340 --> 00:46:27.040 align:middle line:84%
So those prices
can't be different

00:46:27.040 --> 00:46:29.530 align:middle line:84%
when there's no cost to
shipping goods around.

00:46:29.530 --> 00:46:32.860 align:middle line:84%
Now exactly where
the prices are,

00:46:32.860 --> 00:46:34.910 align:middle line:90%
I will show you in a minute.

00:46:34.910 --> 00:46:38.910 align:middle line:84%
But first, let me give
you the theorem called

00:46:38.910 --> 00:46:40.640 align:middle line:90%
Heckscher-Ohlin theorem.

00:46:40.640 --> 00:46:42.640 align:middle line:84%
Suppose initially,
we're in autarky.

00:46:42.640 --> 00:46:44.740 align:middle line:90%
And neither country is trading.

00:46:44.740 --> 00:46:47.470 align:middle line:84%
And the price of the
capital-intensive good

00:46:47.470 --> 00:46:52.150 align:middle line:84%
in the capital-abundant country
will be relatively low--

00:46:52.150 --> 00:46:55.780 align:middle line:84%
relative to the price of
that capital-intensive good

00:46:55.780 --> 00:46:57.550 align:middle line:90%
in the other country.

00:46:57.550 --> 00:47:00.640 align:middle line:84%
This is intuitive in
terms of the economics.

00:47:00.640 --> 00:47:05.230 align:middle line:84%
You have a country that has a
lot of capital and relatively

00:47:05.230 --> 00:47:06.370 align:middle line:90%
little labor.

00:47:06.370 --> 00:47:08.020 align:middle line:90%
That's abundant capital.

00:47:08.020 --> 00:47:10.570 align:middle line:84%
That should drive down
the price of the capital

00:47:10.570 --> 00:47:14.950 align:middle line:84%
input, relative to the
wage of the labor input--

00:47:14.950 --> 00:47:18.400 align:middle line:84%
relative also to
the other country,

00:47:18.400 --> 00:47:21.700 align:middle line:84%
which is abundant in
labor, and should have,

00:47:21.700 --> 00:47:27.070 align:middle line:84%
because there's a lot of labor
around, a relatively low wage.

00:47:27.070 --> 00:47:29.020 align:middle line:84%
So those are the two
statements, the price

00:47:29.020 --> 00:47:32.080 align:middle line:84%
of the capital-intensive good
in the capital-abundant country

00:47:32.080 --> 00:47:35.710 align:middle line:84%
will be lower,
relative to the price

00:47:35.710 --> 00:47:38.500 align:middle line:84%
of that capital-intensive
good in the other country.

00:47:38.500 --> 00:47:40.450 align:middle line:90%
And vise versa for labor.

00:47:40.450 --> 00:47:43.900 align:middle line:84%
The price of the labor-intensive
good in the labor-abundant

00:47:43.900 --> 00:47:48.490 align:middle line:84%
country will be lower,
relative to the price of that

00:47:48.490 --> 00:47:50.740 align:middle line:84%
labor-intensive good
in the other country--

00:47:50.740 --> 00:47:55.190 align:middle line:84%
or in some, when an input is
abundant, it has a low price.

00:47:55.190 --> 00:47:57.220 align:middle line:90%
Now we go to trade.

00:47:57.220 --> 00:47:59.950 align:middle line:84%
We don't allow the
inputs to migrate.

00:47:59.950 --> 00:48:02.740 align:middle line:84%
But we do allow
trade in the goods.

00:48:02.740 --> 00:48:04.210 align:middle line:90%
Think about that first line.

00:48:04.210 --> 00:48:06.430 align:middle line:84%
The price of the
capital-intensive good

00:48:06.430 --> 00:48:10.630 align:middle line:84%
is low, relative to the price
of the capital-intensive

00:48:10.630 --> 00:48:12.230 align:middle line:90%
good in the other country.

00:48:12.230 --> 00:48:15.370 align:middle line:84%
So because it has
a low price, it

00:48:15.370 --> 00:48:17.980 align:middle line:84%
should be a, quote,
"competitive export."

00:48:17.980 --> 00:48:22.300 align:middle line:84%
So the capital-abundant
country will be exporting

00:48:22.300 --> 00:48:24.220 align:middle line:90%
the capital-intensive good.

00:48:24.220 --> 00:48:27.340 align:middle line:84%
The labor-abundant
country will be exporting

00:48:27.340 --> 00:48:29.590 align:middle line:90%
the labor-intensive good.

00:48:29.590 --> 00:48:32.290 align:middle line:84%
And we're going to find
an equilibrium where

00:48:32.290 --> 00:48:36.310 align:middle line:84%
this kind of arbitrage is
no longer profitable, where

00:48:36.310 --> 00:48:39.460 align:middle line:90%
the prices will be the same.

00:48:39.460 --> 00:48:43.870 align:middle line:84%
But the adjustment mechanism
is coming from the possibility

00:48:43.870 --> 00:48:45.470 align:middle line:90%
of exports and imports.

00:48:45.470 --> 00:48:48.220 align:middle line:84%
So let me show you
an example picture.

00:48:48.220 --> 00:48:52.300 align:middle line:84%
Suppose we have country B
here with this production

00:48:52.300 --> 00:48:56.350 align:middle line:84%
possibilities set in the
two goods, G1 and G2.

00:48:56.350 --> 00:48:59.900 align:middle line:84%
Now, I'm not telling you
exactly why it looks like this.

00:48:59.900 --> 00:49:06.700 align:middle line:84%
But it has to do with the fact
that country B is relatively

00:49:06.700 --> 00:49:09.040 align:middle line:90%
abundant in one of the factors.

00:49:09.040 --> 00:49:11.710 align:middle line:84%
You can see, relative
to country A,

00:49:11.710 --> 00:49:14.200 align:middle line:84%
this country can
produce a lot of good 2,

00:49:14.200 --> 00:49:16.420 align:middle line:90%
and relatively little of good 1.

00:49:16.420 --> 00:49:19.030 align:middle line:84%
And that's because of the
different factor intensities.

00:49:19.030 --> 00:49:21.100 align:middle line:84%
The flip side of
that is country A

00:49:21.100 --> 00:49:24.160 align:middle line:84%
over here with its production
possibility frontier.

00:49:24.160 --> 00:49:29.380 align:middle line:84%
And it can produce relatively
more of good 1 than good 2,

00:49:29.380 --> 00:49:31.960 align:middle line:84%
in the sense of enumerating
all the possibilities.

00:49:31.960 --> 00:49:33.430 align:middle line:90%
If you're in autarky--

00:49:33.430 --> 00:49:36.010 align:middle line:84%
now, you remember the
Robinson Crusoe economy

00:49:36.010 --> 00:49:38.980 align:middle line:84%
where we had Robinson
Crusoe producing two goods?

00:49:38.980 --> 00:49:43.630 align:middle line:84%
No trade-- we had, in autarky
therefore, on the island,

00:49:43.630 --> 00:49:46.120 align:middle line:84%
Robinson Crusoe's
indifference curve

00:49:46.120 --> 00:49:49.550 align:middle line:84%
would be tangent to his
production possibility set.

00:49:49.550 --> 00:49:54.490 align:middle line:84%
So this would be the autarky
allocation in country B.

00:49:54.490 --> 00:49:58.260 align:middle line:84%
Likewise, country A, with
a different technology,

00:49:58.260 --> 00:50:02.140 align:middle line:84%
a different island, so to speak,
would have another tangency

00:50:02.140 --> 00:50:05.380 align:middle line:84%
of its preference
indifference curve,

00:50:05.380 --> 00:50:07.510 align:middle line:84%
with a production
possibility set.

00:50:07.510 --> 00:50:12.010 align:middle line:84%
Now, it's kind of easier to
draw with common preferences,

00:50:12.010 --> 00:50:15.340 align:middle line:84%
having the same indifference
curve tangent in both.

00:50:15.340 --> 00:50:18.760 align:middle line:84%
But that's not a necessary
part of the argument.

00:50:18.760 --> 00:50:22.150 align:middle line:84%
All we care about is
tangency for country B

00:50:22.150 --> 00:50:24.070 align:middle line:84%
relative to its
indifference curves,

00:50:24.070 --> 00:50:27.190 align:middle line:84%
and tangency for
country A in autarky,

00:50:27.190 --> 00:50:28.825 align:middle line:84%
relative to its
indifference curves.

00:50:28.825 --> 00:50:31.540 align:middle line:84%
It just happens to be the
same indifference curve.

00:50:31.540 --> 00:50:34.690 align:middle line:84%
Now finally, we go from
autarky to free trade.

00:50:34.690 --> 00:50:36.700 align:middle line:90%
What must be the solution?

00:50:36.700 --> 00:50:42.460 align:middle line:84%
Each country-- B over here
will separate its consumption

00:50:42.460 --> 00:50:43.750 align:middle line:90%
and production problems.

00:50:43.750 --> 00:50:46.420 align:middle line:84%
It will maximize
profits by finding

00:50:46.420 --> 00:50:49.570 align:middle line:84%
the point on its production
possibility frontier

00:50:49.570 --> 00:50:52.960 align:middle line:84%
which gives it the
highest level of profits,

00:50:52.960 --> 00:50:57.220 align:middle line:84%
as captured by this
budget line, really--

00:50:57.220 --> 00:51:01.490 align:middle line:84%
trade line, that emanates
from the new change production

00:51:01.490 --> 00:51:01.990 align:middle line:90%
point.

00:51:01.990 --> 00:51:04.840 align:middle line:84%
And I know the old
production point was autarky

00:51:04.840 --> 00:51:10.180 align:middle line:84%
for country B. It's now shifted
to be giving up some of good 1,

00:51:10.180 --> 00:51:15.610 align:middle line:84%
and producing more of good
2, and then exporting good 2

00:51:15.610 --> 00:51:17.770 align:middle line:90%
and getting more of good 1 back.

00:51:17.770 --> 00:51:21.250 align:middle line:84%
So it specializes
more in production.

00:51:21.250 --> 00:51:23.560 align:middle line:84%
And then achieves
balance in consumption

00:51:23.560 --> 00:51:25.840 align:middle line:90%
by imports and exports.

00:51:25.840 --> 00:51:29.060 align:middle line:84%
And country A down here
is doing the opposite.

00:51:29.060 --> 00:51:30.970 align:middle line:84%
It specialized
more in production

00:51:30.970 --> 00:51:33.970 align:middle line:84%
in the other direction,
more of good 1,

00:51:33.970 --> 00:51:38.260 align:middle line:84%
and then trades in the world
economy, giving up good 1

00:51:38.260 --> 00:51:39.940 align:middle line:90%
and getting good 2.

00:51:39.940 --> 00:51:44.140 align:middle line:84%
And although it's not drawn
here, the exports of good 1

00:51:44.140 --> 00:51:48.820 align:middle line:84%
for country A are exactly
equal to the imports of good 1

00:51:48.820 --> 00:51:53.290 align:middle line:84%
for country B. So the prices
of the goods associated

00:51:53.290 --> 00:51:55.690 align:middle line:84%
with this external
price line are

00:51:55.690 --> 00:51:57.760 align:middle line:84%
the same for both
countries, and have

00:51:57.760 --> 00:52:00.400 align:middle line:84%
the property that, finally,
we have an equilibrium

00:52:00.400 --> 00:52:01.450 align:middle line:90%
in the goods markets.

00:52:01.450 --> 00:52:04.540 align:middle line:84%
In sum, we've now made
the prices endogenous.

00:52:04.540 --> 00:52:08.260 align:middle line:84%
P1 and 2, which were given
throughout 3/4 of the lecture,

00:52:08.260 --> 00:52:12.040 align:middle line:84%
are now determined
internationally by free trade.

00:52:12.040 --> 00:52:14.590 align:middle line:84%
All right, so we
did Heckscher-Ohlin.

00:52:14.590 --> 00:52:18.130 align:middle line:84%
Now we have another theorem,
Stopler-Samuelson theorem.

00:52:18.130 --> 00:52:22.090 align:middle line:84%
In this 2 by 2 by 2 model
with these varying factor

00:52:22.090 --> 00:52:27.260 align:middle line:84%
intensities, if the price
of good i increases,

00:52:27.260 --> 00:52:29.680 align:middle line:84%
then the equilibrium
price of the factor

00:52:29.680 --> 00:52:32.360 align:middle line:84%
that's used more
intensively in good i

00:52:32.360 --> 00:52:36.590 align:middle line:84%
also increases, while the price
of the other factor decreases.

00:52:36.590 --> 00:52:39.080 align:middle line:90%
So let me say it again.

00:52:39.080 --> 00:52:41.570 align:middle line:84%
And let me give the
motivation here.

00:52:41.570 --> 00:52:45.320 align:middle line:84%
We're going from autarky
in each country one

00:52:45.320 --> 00:52:49.280 align:middle line:84%
at a time, with its
internal domestic prices,

00:52:49.280 --> 00:52:52.280 align:middle line:84%
to an equilibrium
in the world economy

00:52:52.280 --> 00:52:55.680 align:middle line:84%
with free trade at
different prices.

00:52:55.680 --> 00:52:59.990 align:middle line:84%
So for country b
here, P1 over P2

00:52:59.990 --> 00:53:04.610 align:middle line:84%
is going down, relative to what
it will be in the free trade

00:53:04.610 --> 00:53:05.450 align:middle line:90%
equilibrium.

00:53:05.450 --> 00:53:07.490 align:middle line:84%
And the reverse is
true for country A.

00:53:07.490 --> 00:53:10.220 align:middle line:84%
So when we go from
autarky to trade,

00:53:10.220 --> 00:53:13.550 align:middle line:84%
we're moving the price
ratio in both countries--

00:53:13.550 --> 00:53:15.690 align:middle line:84%
in different directions,
but we're moving it.

00:53:15.690 --> 00:53:19.190 align:middle line:84%
So let's say, what is the
impact now of moving a price?

00:53:19.190 --> 00:53:23.390 align:middle line:84%
If we increase the price of good
i relative to the other good,

00:53:23.390 --> 00:53:25.790 align:middle line:84%
the equilibrium
price of the factor

00:53:25.790 --> 00:53:29.330 align:middle line:84%
that was used more intensively
in the production of good i

00:53:29.330 --> 00:53:32.210 align:middle line:84%
will increase, while the
price of the other factor

00:53:32.210 --> 00:53:33.930 align:middle line:90%
will decrease.

00:53:33.930 --> 00:53:38.210 align:middle line:84%
OK, so let's go back to a proof
of this in the earlier diagram,

00:53:38.210 --> 00:53:42.200 align:middle line:84%
setting aside the two countries,
kind of not asking for a minute

00:53:42.200 --> 00:53:45.860 align:middle line:84%
where the price comes from--
except that where previously we

00:53:45.860 --> 00:53:48.530 align:middle line:84%
had these isocost
lines crossing,

00:53:48.530 --> 00:53:51.590 align:middle line:84%
the cost lines associated
with P1 and P2--

00:53:51.590 --> 00:53:54.620 align:middle line:84%
we now increase the
price of good 1.

00:53:54.620 --> 00:53:59.090 align:middle line:90%
So C1 equal to P1 is here.

00:53:59.090 --> 00:54:03.680 align:middle line:84%
C1 equal to P prime
1 lies further out.

00:54:03.680 --> 00:54:05.300 align:middle line:84%
It kind of stands
to reason that it

00:54:05.300 --> 00:54:08.150 align:middle line:84%
should lie further out because
we've increased the price.

00:54:08.150 --> 00:54:10.200 align:middle line:90%
And we want cost equal to price.

00:54:10.200 --> 00:54:12.650 align:middle line:84%
So if price is higher,
cost can be higher.

00:54:12.650 --> 00:54:17.330 align:middle line:84%
And cost can be higher by having
higher levels of w1 and w2

00:54:17.330 --> 00:54:18.780 align:middle line:90%
as the input prices.

00:54:18.780 --> 00:54:21.620 align:middle line:84%
So the isocost
line for the price

00:54:21.620 --> 00:54:24.440 align:middle line:84%
when the price increases,
in this case, good 1's price

00:54:24.440 --> 00:54:26.720 align:middle line:90%
increases, shifts outward.

00:54:26.720 --> 00:54:30.380 align:middle line:84%
We haven't done anything to
the price of the other good.

00:54:30.380 --> 00:54:32.150 align:middle line:90%
The C2-- where is it?

00:54:32.150 --> 00:54:35.030 align:middle line:90%
The C2 line is staying constant.

00:54:35.030 --> 00:54:39.170 align:middle line:84%
The C2 isocost line of price
B2 is staying constant.

00:54:39.170 --> 00:54:42.140 align:middle line:84%
However, we need a crossing--
that an equilibrium

00:54:42.140 --> 00:54:44.180 align:middle line:84%
is described by where
the lines cross.

00:54:44.180 --> 00:54:46.700 align:middle line:84%
So we would move from
this initial crossing

00:54:46.700 --> 00:54:48.950 align:middle line:90%
to this second crossing.

00:54:48.950 --> 00:54:51.500 align:middle line:84%
And you can see,
as a consequence

00:54:51.500 --> 00:54:56.390 align:middle line:84%
of the increase in price in P1,
that the price of factor 1--

00:54:56.390 --> 00:54:59.480 align:middle line:90%
good 1 is intensive in factor 1.

00:54:59.480 --> 00:55:02.660 align:middle line:84%
That's the definition that we
were given at the beginning.

00:55:02.660 --> 00:55:05.330 align:middle line:90%
The price of good 1 increases.

00:55:05.330 --> 00:55:07.460 align:middle line:84%
Therefore, the
input, which is used

00:55:07.460 --> 00:55:11.670 align:middle line:84%
intensively in good 1, namely
factor 1, should increase.

00:55:11.670 --> 00:55:13.320 align:middle line:90%
And the other one decreases.

00:55:13.320 --> 00:55:17.390 align:middle line:84%
So this diagram illustrates
the Stopler-Samuelson theorem.

00:55:17.390 --> 00:55:19.940 align:middle line:84%
But again, in the
context of free trade,

00:55:19.940 --> 00:55:22.430 align:middle line:84%
those price movements
come about for a reason.

00:55:22.430 --> 00:55:25.640 align:middle line:84%
Namely, we've gone from
autarky to free trade.

00:55:25.640 --> 00:55:29.000 align:middle line:84%
So you could see earlier which
way the price was moving,

00:55:29.000 --> 00:55:32.870 align:middle line:84%
depending on the initial
country and the autarky.

00:55:32.870 --> 00:55:35.720 align:middle line:84%
Now, although we
know, again, to repeat

00:55:35.720 --> 00:55:37.520 align:middle line:84%
the steps of the
algorithm, we now

00:55:37.520 --> 00:55:39.530 align:middle line:84%
know what happens
to the factor prices

00:55:39.530 --> 00:55:43.040 align:middle line:84%
from this diagram, what happens
to the levels of the inputs,

00:55:43.040 --> 00:55:44.840 align:middle line:90%
and what happens to output.

00:55:44.840 --> 00:55:48.050 align:middle line:84%
Well, we have this,
again, box for production.

00:55:48.050 --> 00:55:51.890 align:middle line:84%
We had the initial allocation
ratio of the factors

00:55:51.890 --> 00:55:53.750 align:middle line:90%
as quantities crossed.

00:55:53.750 --> 00:55:57.620 align:middle line:84%
That is to say, the line for
good 1 and the line for good 2

00:55:57.620 --> 00:55:58.730 align:middle line:90%
crossed.

00:55:58.730 --> 00:56:00.620 align:middle line:90%
And they crossed here.

00:56:00.620 --> 00:56:03.830 align:middle line:84%
But now those factor
prices have changed.

00:56:03.830 --> 00:56:06.200 align:middle line:84%
As a consequence of
the price change,

00:56:06.200 --> 00:56:10.400 align:middle line:84%
the quantity of the
first factor will go down

00:56:10.400 --> 00:56:14.750 align:middle line:84%
because its price has gone up
from country 1's point of view.

00:56:14.750 --> 00:56:19.010 align:middle line:84%
That produces a somewhat
steeper sloped line.

00:56:19.010 --> 00:56:21.770 align:middle line:84%
And the opposite is
going on with country 2.

00:56:21.770 --> 00:56:26.210 align:middle line:84%
So the new equilibrium is
where these now-changed slope

00:56:26.210 --> 00:56:27.830 align:middle line:90%
lines cross.

00:56:27.830 --> 00:56:30.260 align:middle line:84%
And you can actually
see, in this case,

00:56:30.260 --> 00:56:34.340 align:middle line:84%
that firm 1 is producing more
because its isoquant will

00:56:34.340 --> 00:56:34.850 align:middle line:90%
be higher.

00:56:34.850 --> 00:56:37.760 align:middle line:84%
And it's using a higher
level of both inputs.

00:56:37.760 --> 00:56:43.490 align:middle line:84%
And likewise, the production
of good 2 will contract.

00:56:43.490 --> 00:56:47.630 align:middle line:84%
So again, this factor price
equalization theorem is,

00:56:47.630 --> 00:56:52.550 align:middle line:84%
just to restate it, in the
2 by 2 and 2-country model,

00:56:52.550 --> 00:56:56.390 align:middle line:84%
as long as we have this factor
intensity assumption holding

00:56:56.390 --> 00:56:59.300 align:middle line:84%
and the countries are not
completely specialized,

00:56:59.300 --> 00:57:03.110 align:middle line:84%
the equilibrium price
of factors, inputs,

00:57:03.110 --> 00:57:07.790 align:middle line:84%
only depends on the technologies
and on the output prices--

00:57:07.790 --> 00:57:10.640 align:middle line:84%
determined as it may
be, in such a way

00:57:10.640 --> 00:57:15.310 align:middle line:84%
that the prices of the outputs
equals the input costs.

00:57:15.310 --> 00:57:18.760 align:middle line:84%
But now, look, if both
countries face the same prices

00:57:18.760 --> 00:57:20.890 align:middle line:84%
because they trade in
goods, and otherwise there

00:57:20.890 --> 00:57:23.740 align:middle line:84%
would be arbitrage, then
since the prices are

00:57:23.740 --> 00:57:28.210 align:middle line:84%
the same in both countries, we
can zero inside each country,

00:57:28.210 --> 00:57:32.020 align:middle line:84%
and look at the factor prices,
which are clearing the factor

00:57:32.020 --> 00:57:34.250 align:middle line:90%
markets in each country.

00:57:34.250 --> 00:57:37.360 align:middle line:84%
And since each country
has the same technology,

00:57:37.360 --> 00:57:42.100 align:middle line:84%
these equations across the two
goods in each country hold.

00:57:42.100 --> 00:57:44.290 align:middle line:84%
If the prices are the
same on the right hand

00:57:44.290 --> 00:57:47.290 align:middle line:84%
side as a consequence
of free trade,

00:57:47.290 --> 00:57:50.380 align:middle line:84%
then the solution
to the input prices

00:57:50.380 --> 00:57:53.180 align:middle line:84%
has to be the same on
the left hand side.

00:57:53.180 --> 00:57:58.360 align:middle line:84%
So in short, remarkably, we have
not allowed trade in factors--

00:57:58.360 --> 00:58:00.070 align:middle line:90%
no migration.

00:58:00.070 --> 00:58:04.030 align:middle line:84%
But we've managed to equalize
factor prices without migration

00:58:04.030 --> 00:58:07.280 align:middle line:90%
simply by having trade in goods.

00:58:07.280 --> 00:58:11.260 align:middle line:84%
So that's the famous factor
price equalization theorem.

00:58:11.260 --> 00:58:17.560 align:middle line:84%
So vis a vis, the US and Mexico,
allowing the NAFTA, free trade

00:58:17.560 --> 00:58:20.110 align:middle line:84%
in goods, even with
a wall, if I dare

00:58:20.110 --> 00:58:24.070 align:middle line:84%
say, prohibiting
Mexican migration,

00:58:24.070 --> 00:58:29.680 align:middle line:84%
the theorem says that the wages
in Mexico should rise in Mexico

00:58:29.680 --> 00:58:33.620 align:middle line:84%
and fall to the US, to the point
that the wages are the same.

00:58:33.620 --> 00:58:36.610 align:middle line:84%
So the factors
bear consequences.

00:58:36.610 --> 00:58:40.270 align:middle line:84%
It's not necessarily a good
thing that wages of labor

00:58:40.270 --> 00:58:42.190 align:middle line:90%
are falling in the US--

00:58:42.190 --> 00:58:43.690 align:middle line:90%
not good for those firms.

00:58:43.690 --> 00:58:46.540 align:middle line:84%
We have to come back
to those households.

00:58:46.540 --> 00:58:48.610 align:middle line:84%
We have to come back
to the welfare theorems

00:58:48.610 --> 00:58:52.130 align:middle line:84%
to think about the winners
and losers from trade.

00:58:52.130 --> 00:58:56.440 align:middle line:84%
The point here only is that you
can see why there is sometimes

00:58:56.440 --> 00:59:00.490 align:middle line:84%
resistance to trade because
trade does have consequences

00:59:00.490 --> 00:59:01.910 align:middle line:90%
for factor prices.

00:59:01.910 --> 00:59:05.440 align:middle line:84%
Hence, for the welfare of the
providers of those factors,

00:59:05.440 --> 00:59:09.100 align:middle line:84%
depending on whether they're
capitalists that own wealth,

00:59:09.100 --> 00:59:12.160 align:middle line:84%
capital that's used in
machinery and so on,

00:59:12.160 --> 00:59:17.100 align:middle line:84%
versus laborers that have
only their labor endowment.

00:59:17.100 --> 00:59:20.400 align:middle line:84%
OK, so next time we're going
to go with this kind of theorem

00:59:20.400 --> 00:59:22.560 align:middle line:90%
back to the Thai villages.

00:59:22.560 --> 00:59:25.470 align:middle line:84%
And then we're going to go,
in the subsequent lecture,

00:59:25.470 --> 00:59:28.900 align:middle line:84%
to the US, and
explore these ideas.

00:59:28.900 --> 00:59:30.900 align:middle line:90%
OK, that's all I have for today.

00:59:30.900 --> 00:59:33.470 align:middle line:90%
OK, thank you very much.

00:59:33.470 --> 00:59:41.000 align:middle line:90%